body.name: Rising Moon: A Jesse McDermitt Novel (Caribbean Adventure Series Book 19)
body.description: On Grassy Key, things aren’t as idyllic as they seem. The quiet, sleepy community has been awakened. A young woman with strong ties to the community is missing.A local craftsman, the last person to see the girl, is questioned and released. The girl’s friends are interviewed. Nobody knows what happened to Cobie, except that she left for work one day and didn’t arrive. The only lead is the girl’s car, parked where she worked. But it provides no clues and nobody saw anything.Days go by. Then weeks. The case grows cold.The employer of the girl’s mother knows Jesse McDermitt, a retired Marine and reputed government spook. Jesse leans on people the way only he can and soon finds there is a lot more to the abduction than anyone knew.Does he find the missing girl? Does he survive what he uncovers? Find out in this 19th novel in Wayne Stinnett’s wildly popular Jesse McDermitt Caribbean Adventure Series.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 28, 2020
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars This one will go down as one of the series best
reviews.reviewText: This book is hard to write a review for. There are so many spinning circles and return characters to keep up with. But they all apear in the right places at the right times and it all works. I will freely admit that I have felt like there was a drop in the quality of the story telling and especially in the wrap it all up in a neat clean bow finishes of the Jesse McDermitt series over the last six or so books. Although this one had a wrap it up with the nice clean bow finish, it actually fit this time. And I enjoyed the weaving of more of Jesse's back story through the character of Tank. I am also looking forward to at least a few more appearances of Tank in future books.Read this book. If it's the first time for you reading a Jesse McDermitt book, go back and read the series from the beginning. The characters will become like family to you and you will better understand the interaction between all the characters in this story. I am actually looking forward again to what comes next for Jesse and crew. That hasn't happened for a while.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on September 29, 2022
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars A Review of Rising Moon: Jesse McDermitt Book 19
reviews.reviewText: This was a very different story involving the disappearance of a beautiful young girl who had gone to pick up a body surfing board and then go to work at K-Mart. She never arrived, and the police having no leads wrote it off as she must have taken off. When nothing changed on the investigation Cobies Mom talked to her boss and he asked Jesse if he could help. Jesse met with Donna, Cobies mom and told her he would look into it. The trail was linked to big time drug dealers and it didn’t take long for Jesse to make some connections as to who was responsible. Great story with some chilling moments not unlike those that have been vested upon kidnapped young women used as sex slaves in many parts of our world.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on February 21, 2023
reviews.reviewText: Once again, Rising Moon, provides a real fun vehicle for Jessie McDermott and all the things that he does and the various schemes he gets into and now he's finally met someone and now he's married it's a very very good story I look forward to the next book.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on October 11, 2023
reviews.reviewText: Continuing story of a longtime marine friend \ Tank! Thank God Jesse takes a chance at marriage when in his past his wife was taken away within 24 hours after his wedding g ceramony. Its refreshing to know that good wins out in the end. Oh yeah, love the dogs!

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 24, 2023
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars That's more like it!
reviews.reviewText: After having read, and been disappointed with, "Wayward Sons", I needed a "fix" for some Stinnett-only writing with Jesse and friends. Well, "Rising Moon" did the trick! It is vintage Stinnett with all the adventure, humor, suspense and happy/dad feelings one has come to expect. I confess to having to wipe my eyes a little more than usual!

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on January 3, 2021
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Another Enjoyable Interlude With Jesse
reviews.reviewText: This episode in Jesse's life has a little bit of a different feel. There has been a time-hop that I enjoyed, more in the present day. Jesse is a little older, has become a family man which makes him think before acting. However, when he sets a plan in motion, it is as exciting as ever. The part I most enjoyed was the return of Owen "Tank" Tankersley which provides a window into his world, some of which is very poignant. He and Jesse embark on fulfilling Tank's bucket list, while setting a rescue in motion. Charity Styles also makes an appearance to assist in this multi-location, mobile and time sensitive effort. I had some mixed emotions with the outcome, but I am not going to take off a point for that .... it's a personal thing .... others will love it. I'm looking forward to Rising Tide!

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 22, 2020
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars The Gold Standard
reviews.reviewText: Once again, Mr. Stinnett has written another book that restores my faith in the good versus evil among our fellow man & inspires the reader to set their eyes on the horizon in search of adventure. This series is a fine example of why Wayne Stinnett has earned his spot among great adventure writers such as Cussler. I prefer these books due to their more relatable locations. I spend a lot of time on the water off my home state of South Carolina but live further inland in the Appalachia Foothills. The past year of uncertainty, lockdowns & other insanity has made it difficult to even make the 3+ hour drive to the intracoastal, but reading Jesse McDermitt’s adventures have become a happy escape on their own. I recommend this book & I can not wait for more!Fair winds & following seas,T. Hayes

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United States on December 23, 2020
reviews.reviewTitle: 5.0 out of 5 stars Best Jesse McDermitt novel yet. They just keep getting better and better.
reviews.reviewText: I very rarely give a 5 star review. But this book demands that I do so. I have read every Jesse McDermitt novel in the series and pre-ordered #20 as soon as it was available for pre-order. Every one of those books has been a joy to read, but this time Wayne Stinnett has outdone himself. This is the best of the series yet. I finished the book in under 24 hours simply because I could not put it down. Character development if full and rich. You know these people and like most of them. The action is fast paced and has you on the edge of your seat. I especially liked that some favorite characters were brought back into this story. Can't wait to read "Rising Tide" due out in April.

Another Adrenaline high with a continuous build of energy, leading to a happy but bittersweet finish. Realistically demonstrating that one can't 'wish life perfect'. Bravo Sir, Jesse is the embodiment of that reality.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United Kingdom on December 23, 2020
reviews.reviewText: What a rollercoaster of a book, from the start to the finish. Jessie was his brilliant best doing what he has always done and killing off the bad guys into the bargain, then splitting up the gold. Very interesting to find out about Tank and the US Marine Corps.It was lovely to read about all his contemporaries too and at last he has found someone to hopefully live with for the rest of his life (Wayne) to take note!!

This was a book I couldn't put down. The action and mystery surrounding the entire story was riveting and totally captivating. Great characters with lots of laughter and a bit of romance. Fantastic story and well written.

reviews.reviewDate: Reviewed in the United Kingdom on March 6, 2022
reviews.reviewTitle: One of the best so far
reviews.reviewText: I've read all previous 19 Jesse books and this is one of the best. Wayne is a excellent storyteller and in Jesse, he truly created a remarkable hero.

reviews.reviewTitle: Another great read in the Jessie series
reviews.reviewText: Maybe one of the best yet. Any book that gets me emotional reading it has to have something special, and this book was like that in several places. Tank is an awesome addition.
